This paper presents a new algorithm for a non-blocking $k$-ary search tree that supports range queries. The algorithm uses compare-and-swap (CAS) operations and tolerates crash failures. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on data structures and algorithms for search trees, which suggests that it could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of single-word CAS operations, which is a common technique in operating systems (cs.OS) and concurrency (cs.PL) research. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of the algorithm and compares it to other algorithms, which suggests that it could also belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category.
